0.1 Market data¶

In [4]:
def pull_stock_data(ticker:str,
                    start="2004-01-01",
                    end="2019-01-01",
                    freq="daily") -> pd.DataFrame:
    yahoo_financials = YahooFinancials(ticker)
    data = yahoo_financials.get_historical_price_data(start, end, freq)
    df = pd.DataFrame(data[ticker]["prices"])
    df.index = df.formatted_date.astype("datetime64")
    df.index.name = "date"
    return df.asfreq("D").fillna(method="ffill")

Simple Returns

$$ R_t = \frac{p_t}{p_{t-1}} - 1 $$

Log-Returns

$$ \ln{(R_t)} = \ln{(1+R_{t})} = \ln{(\frac{p_t}{p_{t-1}})} $$$$ \leftrightarrow \ln{(1+R(t))} $$

Monthly volatility

$$ \frac{1}{21} \sum_{t=1}^{21} \ln{(1+R(t))}^{2} $$

#Scrape the S&P500 company tickers and their names
def get_tickers():
    resp = requests.get('http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_S%26P_500_companies')
    soup = bs.BeautifulSoup(resp.text, 'lxml')
    table = soup.find('table', {'class': 'wikitable sortable'})
    data = []
    for row in table.findAll('tr')[1:]:
        ticker = row.findAll('td')[0].text
        name = row.findAll('td')[1].text
        data.append({"ticker" : ticker.rstrip("\n"), "name" : name})
    return data

Now I will remove things like "Incorporated, Inc, Inc., Corporation, Corp., Group" since those suffixes are commonly irrelevant when quering for information on the web.

In [18]:
unwanted_suffixes = ["," , "Inc.", "Inc", "Incorporated",
                     "Corporation", "Corp", "Corp.",
                     "Co.", "Co", "& Co", "Group", "Gp.", "& Co.",
                     "Company", "plc", "Technology", "Technologies",
                    "Laboratories", "Pharmaceuticals", "Systems", "Holdings", "Ltd.", "Limited",
                    ".com", "Communications", "Industries", "International", "Trust", "Services", "Ltd"
                    "Class A", "Class C", "Class B"]
for company in companies:
    name = company["name"]
    for stopword in unwanted_suffixes:
        if name.endswith(stopword):
            company["name"] = name[:-len(stopword)].rstrip()
            break

In [20]:
def pull_query_data(Q:list, company) -> pd.DataFrame:
    ticker, name = company["ticker"], company["name"]
    Q = [ticker, name] + [_+" "+suffix for _ in [ticker, name] for suffix in Q]
    dfs = []
    for q in Q:
        data = collect_data(q)
        dfs.append(data)
    df = pd.merge(dfs[0], dfs[1], left_index=True, right_index=True)
    for x in dfs[2:]:
        df = pd.merge(df, x, left_index=True, right_index=True)
    return df

For the query set, I propose $Q \gets \{ \text{"stock"}, \text{"share"}, \text{"annual report"} \}$ such that for each company there are $(\vert Q \vert \ \times 2) + 2$ query series'.

For any company I therefore collect $\vert Q \vert = 8$ query series.

In [ ]:
#Define a Query list
Q = ["stock", "share"]
#Append query data
for company in companies:
    data = pull_query_data(Q, company)
    data.columns = [i.replace(": (Worldwide)", "") for i in data.columns]
    company["query_data"] = data

Query data imputation rule (OUTDATED)¶

Since I want to compute pct_changefor the queries, I need to impute zero-values.

For a given value $x_i \in q \ \ \forall \ \ q \in Q$ it is known that

$$ x_i = \begin{cases} 0, & \text{if $x_i < T$}\\ x_i, & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} $$

where $T$ is a threshold value which is not public. Altough it is possible to reversly find $T$, I think that simply imputing $T$ will yield reasonable results.

Possibilities on how to impute :

  1. Use last value
    • Reasonable since this is a time series
  2. Gaussian Noise around $0$
  3. Use a value which is just a little bit smaller than the smallest value within the series.
